title: For Sale:  Native American Flint Knife
postcontent:
Flint knife with Deer antler handle.  


Knives
Native Americans often made knives out of stone like chert and flint by using a "chipped-stone" technique, according to Missouri State University. The worker struck the chert or flint with another stone, causing chips to fly off. Over time, the knife's edge sharpened. Workers used the same technique to make arrowheads, which were small, pointy knives that the worker attached to a shaft to make an arrow.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Walther PP .32acp
postcontent: For sale or trade is a Walther PP chambered for the .32 acp cartridge, from the info I've gathered the pistol was most likely brought back from a returning GI after WW2, it has mismatched numbers and no import stamp or nazi / proof marks on it, the serial numbers are just a little after what's listed for the WW2 production, these pistols were commonly referred to as cigarette guns because Gi's often traded cigs to Walther employees who would then assemble the GI a pistol from the parts bins. I've shot about a box and a half of shells thru it and it never had a jam or misfire but the hammer will sometimes follow the slide, since it's double action it won't slow you down much, it's worse with factory ammo than with some reloads I got with the gun, it has not fired out of battery. I've read it is a common problem and chances are a new recoil spring and hammer strut spring will probably fix it but I haven't bought them yet to try. The finish is thin and has a nice patina. I do have what is probably the original Walther mag for it also. While the price is negotiable, I won't take $100.00 for it, so mplivers and the rest of you don't need to ask. I will trade depending on item offered but if your not serious about trading don't bother asking. Missouri residents only please. Thanks.

title: For Sale:  Mosin Nagant 91/30 7.62x54R
postcontent:
I have a nice arsenal refinished Mosin Nagant 91/30 that I am looking to sell. I have a bit of a collection of Mosin Nagants and this one is of little collector value but is in great shape as a shooter. The blueing is basically 100% and its got good strong rifling. It is all matching except for the floor plate which has a serial number crossed out and a matching one engraved next to it. I cant read the date on it because it was not deeply engraved enough, but im pretty sure it is a war time production around 1943. Like I said, its not one of collector value but would be a great shooter. I have enough shooters around and want to get some extra money to go and buy another for the collection :). 

If you dont know about Mosin Nagant Rifles, they are extremely rugged rifles used by the Russian military from the late part of the 19th century until they were phased out by the SKS and AK in the mid 20th century. They were still used by other communist countries until much more recently. They fire the 7.62x54R round which is one of the least expensive and most easily obtainable military surplus rounds available. This is a great "end of the world" type gun to squiral away in the closet with a box of ammo because it is low in cost and always reliable. Anyhow. Let me know if your interested.

title: For Sale/Trade:  WTS 1895 Nagant Revolver 7.62 Tokarev!
postcontent:
I have an 1895 Revolver that has a cylinder that takes 7.62 tokarev rounds. I've looked into and it's possible it's a factory conversion but I doubt it. As is it is UNSAFE TO FIRE but if someone were more savvy with reloading equipment you could possibly make lower powered Tokarev rounds and be able to fire the gun much cheaper than any other Nagant revolver as 7.62 Tokarev is a lot more common and a lot easier to reload for than the Nagant original rounds and .32 S&W long. You could also buy a replacement cylinder to shoot .32 ACP

As the condition goes it's one of the best I've ever seen a Nagant revolver in. It indexes perfectly, it's never failed to fire for me and everything is very tight. 

As history goes I've looked into it and found these markings.


East German Triangle
Izhevsk 1945r
bakelite grips
Late Russian Sights

I bought this gun last year at a gun shop in Corbin KY and want to sell because I don't have the reloading equipment to fire the gun safely. I bought it not knowing it was a Tok conversion.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson Model 2  .32 rimfire
postcontent:
This is a American Civil War era firearm, with its original holster.

S&W Model 2  .32 rimfire

It seems to fall between a type 3 and a type 4 according to 
( http://www.model2project.com ) my guess is a type 3 due to the size of the serial number stamp.

There is some pitting on the barrel and some lighter pitting around the cylinder and frame, the grips look great. The internals are still tight and operate very smoothly. The hammer pulls back smooth, & locks up tight, the trigger pull is crisp and has zero creep. The top hinge is 95% tight with very slight amount of looseness noted. The bottom lock is slightly loose, but has no signs of attempted repairs. The guns finish is all original with no evidence of restoration. One thing to note however, an artificial
ejector rod was inserted, but is not in any way made permanent or caused the frame to look altered. 

Also this seems to be a S&W run production, no markings have been found that would indicate it was made for any corporations of the time

I can take and email pictures. If a strong interest is noted I can also take high-res microscopic photos of the surface, and surface stamped markings
if requested.

Please note: I am not a historical firearms expert and I am not qualified to make any certifications of authenticity. This is why I offer the high res imaging so you can do your own research.
